 wird in Anschluss an die von Virginia Woolf in ihrem Essay "A Room of One's Own" schon 1929 beschriebenen Herausforderungen für das literarische Schreiben von Frauen auch die Frage nach Bedingungen und Widersprüchen künstlerischer Kreativität gestellt. Mit Beiträgen zu Selma Lagerlöf (1909), Grazia Deledda (1926), Sigrid Undset (1928), Pearl S. Buck (1938), Gabriela Mistral (1945), Nelly Sachs (1966), Nadine Gordimer (1991), Toni Morrison (1993), Wisława Szymborska (1996), Elfriede Jelinek (2004), Doris Lessing (2007), Herta Müller (2009), Alice Munro (2013), Swetlana Alexijewitsch (2015)  aThis volume presents the 14 female winners of the Nobel Prize in Literature, e.g. Lagerlöf, Sachs, Jelinek, Müller, Munro. Contributions offers exemplary readings of chosen works, while outlining the intellectual profile of each author. They also tackle the questions of female writing and canon formation, and interrogate the conditions and contradictions of artistic creativity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aLiterature (General). 0aLiteraturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNobel Prizes. 0aWomen Nobel Prize winnersvBiography. 4aGender. 4aKanonisierungsprozess. 4aLiteraturgeschichte. 4aNobelpreis. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh  aCanon Formation.  aLiterary History.  aNobel Prize.  aWomen Writers.1 aBirke, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrokoff, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnderwitz, An